   <abstract >The Buddhist Churches of America (BCA) is the largest and oldest Japanese American Buddhist organization. While scholars have recognized the several ways the BCA has assimilated to American cultural and Protestant religious norms and standards, less addressed are the direct causal influences for such assimilation beyond broad appeals to American culture or anti-Asian sentiment. This project explores the material mechanisms through which cultural and political discourse is mediated to religio-racial minority communities, especially through law and bureaucratic administration. I argue that Japanese American Buddhist encounters with American law, bureaucracy, and language were foundational to the transformations of Pure Land Buddhism in America. In order to abide in the American context, both culturally and legally, Buddhist churches engaged necessary legal statutes and bureaucratic paperwork, which impressed upon them state definitions of race, religion, and citizenship. Due to the nature of American legal structures, Japanese American Buddhists encountered a wide range of paperwork to signify their religiosity, rights, and legal statuses, especially regarding land ownership, the tax system, citizenship or residential status, and immigration legislation, among others. However, the variable nature of American law and bureaucracy creates unique opportunities for religious, legal, and political negotiation. Religious incorporation is a potent site of research and analysis for this dynamic as it exemplifies the legal logics and bureaucratic mechanisms operating at the interface of government and governed populations. The multifaceted and flexible nature of state bureaucracy and law, as well the problems and politics of linguistic translation, allowed Japanese American Buddhists to assert their right to belong in the American religious and legal landscape. Shaped by the experience of encountering rapid social change impositions of imperial power in Meiji-era Japan, Japanese American Buddhists adapted to the imperial ideologies and administrative structures of their new context, thereby producing a unique American expression of Pure Land Buddhism.</abstract>
